### Describe the bug

`HeadlessUnitTestSession` has a failure-amplification reliability defect: a single unhandled exception thrown during a work item's **cleanup stage** kills the internal dispatch consumer loop silently. The work item's own `TaskCompletionSource` never transitions, and **every subsequent `Dispatch` call also never completes**. Nothing is reported to the caller — a full test suite simply stops making progress while all executed tests remain green.

The **application-construction** variant of this problem was fixed by #21688 (included in 12.1.0): exceptions from `EnsureIsolatedApplication` / `EnsureSharedApplication` are now routed to the TCS. However, the same amplification structure remains for exceptions thrown during **cleanup** (and any other unprotected work-item lifecycle stage). Verified against the shipped 12.1.0 binaries.

Any user can be affected when an exception escapes from an unprotected work-item lifecycle stage. In our case (a ~650-test xUnit v3 suite), roughly 1 in 8 full runs stalled with 8 UI tests "running" forever and no failure reported; the trigger was an intermittent platform re-initialization race under `PerTest` isolation (that particular exception now surfaces as a test failure on 12.1.0 thanks to #21688, but any cleanup-stage exception still reproduces the permanent hang deterministically, see below).


### To Reproduce

```csharp
using Avalonia;
using Avalonia.Headless;
using Avalonia.Threading;

var session = HeadlessUnitTestSession.StartNew(typeof(Application), AvaloniaTestIsolationLevel.PerAssembly);

// 1) Sanity: a normal dispatch completes.
var sanity = await session.Dispatch(() => 42, CancellationToken.None).WaitAsync(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(10));
Console.WriteLine($"1) sanity dispatch: completed ({sanity})");

// 2) Poison: the dispatched action itself succeeds, but leaves a job on the dispatcher
//    queue that throws. The job runs during the work item's cleanup stage
//    (Dispatcher.UIThread.RunJobs() inside the finally), outside any try/catch that
//    routes exceptions to the work item's TaskCompletionSource.
var poison = session.Dispatch(
    () => Dispatcher.UIThread.Post(
        () => throw new InvalidOperationException("poison: thrown by a posted job during cleanup RunJobs")),
    CancellationToken.None);
try { await poison.WaitAsync(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(10)); Console.WriteLine("2) poison dispatch: completed"); }
catch (TimeoutException) { Console.WriteLine($"2) poison dispatch: NOT completed after 10s (Status={poison.Status})"); }

// 3) Any subsequent dispatch never completes.
var next = session.Dispatch(() => 1, CancellationToken.None);
try { var v = await next.WaitAsync(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(10)); Console.WriteLine($"3) subsequent dispatch: completed ({v})"); }
catch (TimeoutException) { Console.WriteLine($"3) subsequent dispatch: NOT completed after 10s (Status={next.Status}) => permanent hang"); }
```

Observed output on Avalonia.Headless **12.1.0** (identical for `PerAssembly` and `PerTest`):

```
1) sanity dispatch: completed (42)
2) poison dispatch: NOT completed after 10s (Task.Status=WaitingForActivation) — its own TCS never transitioned
3) subsequent dispatch: NOT completed after 10s (Task.Status=WaitingForActivation) => permanent hang reproduced
[UnobservedTaskException] poison: exception thrown by a posted job during cleanup RunJobs
```

The only trace of the original exception is a `TaskScheduler.UnobservedTaskException` after a GC — nothing surfaces to the `Dispatch` caller or the test framework.


### Expected behavior

- A work item's `Task` must always transition (success / failure / cancellation), regardless of which lifecycle stage throws.
- If the consumer loop cannot continue, pending and subsequent `Dispatch` calls should fail fast with the stored cause (e.g., `ObjectDisposedException`-style), never hang forever.


### Avalonia version

12.0.4 and 12.1.0 

### OS

Windows

### Additional context

- Possibly the concrete mechanism behind reports like #21467 (tests stuck awaiting `Dispatch`).
- Real-world trigger we hit on 12.0.4: intermittent `InvalidOperationException` ("The calling thread cannot access this object...") from per-dispatch platform re-initialization under default `PerTest` isolation. On 12.0.4 that exception killed the loop via the then-unprotected construction stage (fixed by #21688); the cleanup stage shown above still reproduces the hang on 12.1.0 deterministically.
- Workarounds we currently use, for other affected users: pin `AvaloniaTestIsolationLevel.PerAssembly`, plus a reflection-based watchdog on the session's private `_dispatchTask` that calls `Environment.FailFast(cause)` when the loop faults (turns the silent hang into an immediate diagnosable crash), plus MTP HangDump as a last-resort activity timeout.

### Describe the bug

When one has a two-way binding with `UpdateSourceTrigger=Explicit`, the target value can be changed and will not be written back to the source until `UpdateSource` is called. If instead `UpdateTarget` is called to undo the change and re-read the source value back to the target, the source value will not be written and the value will remain unchanged.

### To Reproduce

A failing unit test is worth a thousand words:

```csharp
[Fact]
public void TwoWay_Explicit_Should_Update_Target_On_Call_To_UpdateTarget()
{
	var data = new ViewModel { StringValue = "foo" };
	var (target, expression) = CreateTargetAndExpression<ViewModel, string?>(
		o => o.StringValue,
		mode: BindingMode.TwoWay,
		source: data,
		updateSourceTrigger: UpdateSourceTrigger.Explicit);

	Assert.Equal("foo", target.String);
	Assert.Equal("foo", data.StringValue);

	target.String = "bar";

	Assert.Equal("bar", target.String);
	Assert.Equal("foo", data.StringValue);

	// UpdateTarget forces a transfer from source to target, discarding the
	// value set on the target.
	expression.UpdateTarget();

	Assert.Equal("foo", target.String);
	Assert.Equal("foo", data.StringValue);
}
```

### Expected behavior

The source value is written to the target when `UpdateTarget` is called.

### Avalonia version

master

### OS

_No response_

### Additional context

Failing test added to https://github.com/AvaloniaUI/Avalonia/tree/fixes%2F21746-update-target-explicit.

### Is your feature request related to a problem? Please describe.

When using Avalonia on Linux with the Framebuffer backend and LibInput, physically disconnecting and reconnecting an input device (in my case, touchscreen) results in the device being completely ignored after reconnection. The application must be restarted to restore input.

### Describe the solution you'd like

I propose adding support for libinput_udev_create_context in addition to the existing libinput_path_create_context. The udev context automatically discovers devices and supports hotplug out of the box.

### Describe alternatives you've considered

There is an alternative that I currently use: run Avalonia app in a lightweight WM. 

### Additional context

Here is the C snippet that I used to test my theory. 
```c
#include <stdio.h>
#include <stdlib.h>
#include <fcntl.h>      
#include <unistd.h>    
#include <poll.h>      
#include <libinput.h>
#include <libudev.h>
static int open_restricted(const char *path, int flags, void *user_data) {
    int fd = open(path, flags);
    return fd < 0 ? -1 : fd;
}
static void close_restricted(int fd, void *user_data) {
    close(fd);
}
static const struct libinput_interface interface = {
    .open_restricted = open_restricted,
    .close_restricted = close_restricted,
};
int main(void) {
    struct libinput *li;
    struct udev *udev = udev_new();

    if (!udev) {
        fprintf(stderr, "Failed to initialize udev\n");
        return 1;
    }
    li = libinput_udev_create_context(&interface, NULL, udev);
    if (!li) {
        fprintf(stderr, "Failed to initialize libinput context\n");
        udev_unref(udev);
        return 1;
    }

    int rc = libinput_udev_assign_seat(li, "seat0");
    if (rc != 0) {
        fprintf(stderr, "Failed to assign seat0. Are you running as root?\n");
        libinput_unref(li);
        udev_unref(udev);
        return 1;
    }
    int fd = libinput_get_fd(li);
    printf("Listening for events (including hotplug). Press Ctrl+C to exit.\n");
    printf("Please disconnect and reconnect your input device...\n");
    while (1) {
        libinput_dispatch(li);

        struct libinput_event *ev;
        while ((ev = libinput_get_event(li)) != NULL) {
            enum libinput_event_type type = libinput_event_get_type(ev);

            if (type == LIBINPUT_EVENT_DEVICE_ADDED) {
                struct libinput_device *dev = libinput_event_get_device(ev);
                printf("[HOTPLUG] Device ADDED! (Name: %s)\n", libinput_device_get_name(dev));
            } else if (type == LIBINPUT_EVENT_DEVICE_REMOVED) {
                struct libinput_device *dev = libinput_event_get_device(ev);
                printf("[HOTPLUG] Device REMOVED! (Name: %s)\n", libinput_device_get_name(dev));
            } else if (type >= LIBINPUT_EVENT_TOUCH_DOWN && type <= LIBINPUT_EVENT_TOUCH_CANCEL) {
                printf("[INPUT] Touch event detected!\n");
            } else if (type >= LIBINPUT_EVENT_POINTER_MOTION && type <= LIBINPUT_EVENT_POINTER_AXIS) {
                printf("[INPUT] Pointer (mouse) event!\n");
            }

            libinput_event_destroy(ev);
            libinput_dispatch(li);
        }

        struct pollfd pfd;
        pfd.fd = fd;
        pfd.events = POLLIN;

        poll(&pfd, 1, 1000); 
    }
    libinput_unref(li);
    udev_unref(udev);
    return 0;
}
```

There might be potential issues:
- avalonia would need to import functions from udev library;
- libinput might not apply the calibration matrix of the device on reattach


Solution would look something like this:
```csharp

namespace Avalonia.LinuxFramebuffer.Input.LibInput
{
    public enum LibInputContextType
    {
        /// <summary>
        /// Uses libinput_path_create_context. Requires explicit device paths. 
        /// Does not support hotplug (device reconnect).
        /// </summary>
        Path,

        /// <summary>
        /// Uses libinput_udev_create_context. Automatically discovers devices via udev.
        /// Fully supports hotplug (device reconnect).
        /// </summary>
        Udev,
    }

    public sealed class LibInputBackendOptions
    {
        /// <summary>
        /// List of event device paths to monitor (e.g., /dev/input/eventX).
        /// Used only when <see cref="ContextType"/> is set to <see cref="LibInputContextType.Path"/>.
        /// </summary>
        public IReadOnlyList<string>? Events { get; init; } = null;

        /// <summary>
        /// Type of initialized libinput context. 
        /// Defaults to <see cref="LibInputContextType.Path"/> for backward compatibility.
        /// </summary>
        public LibInputContextType ContextType { get; init; } = LibInputContextType.Path;

        /// <summary>
        /// The udev seat name to assign (e.g., "seat0"). 
        /// Used only when <see cref="ContextType"/> is set to <see cref="LibInputContextType.Udev"/>.
        /// If null, "seat0" is used by default.
        /// </summary>
        public string? UdevSeat { get; init; } = null;
    }

    public partial class LibInputBackend : IInputBackend, IDisposable
    {
        private IScreenInfoProvider? _screen;
        private IInputRoot? _inputRoot;
        private const string LibInput = nameof(LinuxFramebuffer) + "/" + nameof(Input) + "/" + nameof(LibInput);
        private const string LibUdev = "libudev.so.1";

        private Action<RawInputEventArgs>? _onInput;
        private readonly LibInputBackendOptions? _options;

        private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;
        private Thread? _inputThread;


        public LibInputBackend()
        {
            _options = default;
        }

        public LibInputBackend(LibInputBackendOptions options)
        {
            _options = options;
        }

        private IInputRoot InputRoot
            => _inputRoot ?? throw new InvalidOperationException($"{nameof(InputRoot)} hasn't been set");

        private unsafe void InputThread(IntPtr ctx, LibInputBackendOptions options, IntPtr udevCtx, CancellationToken token)
        {
            var fd = libinput_get_fd(ctx);
            var screenOrientation = _screen is ISurfaceOrientation surfaceOrientation ? surfaceOrientation.Orientation : SurfaceOrientation.Rotation0;

            float[] matrix = screenOrientation switch
            {
                SurfaceOrientation.Rotation90 => [0, 1, 0, -1, 0, 1],
                SurfaceOrientation.Rotation180 => [-1, 0, 1, 0, -1, 1],
                SurfaceOrientation.Rotation270 => [0, -1, 1, 1, 0, 0],
                _ => [1, 0, 0, 0, 1, 0],    // Normal
            };

            if (options.ContextType == LibInputContextType.Path)
            {
                // Original behavior: add devices immediately
                var paths = options.Events ?? Directory.GetFiles("/dev/input", "event*");
                foreach (var path in paths)
                {
                    var device = libinput_path_add_device(ctx, path);
                    if (device != IntPtr.Zero)
                    {
                        libinput_device_config_calibration_set_matrix(device, matrix);
                    }
                }
            }

            while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                IntPtr ev;
                libinput_dispatch(ctx);
                while ((ev = libinput_get_event(ctx)) != IntPtr.Zero)
                {
                    var type = libinput_event_get_type(ev);

                    if (type == LibInputEventType.LIBINPUT_EVENT_DEVICE_ADDED)
                    {
                        var device = libinput_event_get_device(ev);
                        if (device != IntPtr.Zero)
                        {
                            // Reapply calibration matrix to newly connected (hotplugged) devices
                            libinput_device_config_calibration_set_matrix(device, matrix);
                        }
                    }
                    else if (type >= LibInputEventType.LIBINPUT_EVENT_TOUCH_DOWN &&
                             type <= LibInputEventType.LIBINPUT_EVENT_TOUCH_CANCEL)
                    {
                        HandleTouch(ev, type);
                    }
                    else if (type >= LibInputEventType.LIBINPUT_EVENT_POINTER_MOTION &&
                             type <= LibInputEventType.LIBINPUT_EVENT_POINTER_AXIS)
                    {
                        HandlePointer(ev, type);
                    }

                    libinput_event_destroy(ev);
                    libinput_dispatch(ctx);
                }

                if (token.IsCancellationRequested) break;

                var pfd = new PollFd { fd = fd, events = 1 };
                // 10ms timeout to allow checking the cancellation token periodically
                NativeUnsafeMethods.poll(&pfd, new IntPtr(1), 10);
            }

            // Cleanup when thread exits
            libinput_unref(ctx);
            if (udevCtx != IntPtr.Zero)
            {
                udev_unref(udevCtx);
            }
        }

        private void ScheduleInput(RawInputEventArgs ev) => _onInput?.Invoke(ev);

        public void Initialize(IScreenInfoProvider screen, Action<RawInputEventArgs> onInput)
        {
            _screen = screen;
            _onInput = onInput;
            _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();

            var options = _options ?? new LibInputBackendOptions();

            IntPtr udevCtx = IntPtr.Zero;
            IntPtr ctx;

            if (options.ContextType == LibInputContextType.Udev)
            {
                try
                {
                    udevCtx = udev_new();
                    if (udevCtx == IntPtr.Zero)
                    {
                        throw new InvalidOperationException("Failed to initialize udev context.");
                    }

                    // Assuming s_Interface is defined in the LibInputNativeUnsafeMethods partial class
                    ctx = libinput_udev_create_context(in s_Interface, IntPtr.Zero, udevCtx);
                    if (ctx == IntPtr.Zero)
                    {
                        udev_unref(udevCtx);
                        throw new InvalidOperationException("Failed to initialize libinput context via udev.");
                    }

                    string seat = options.UdevSeat ?? "seat0";
                    int rc = libinput_udev_assign_seat(ctx, seat);
                    if (rc != 0)
                    {
                        libinput_unref(ctx);
                        udev_unref(udevCtx);
                        throw new InvalidOperationException($"Failed to assign udev seat '{seat}'. Are you running with appropriate permissions?");
                    }
                }
                catch (DllNotFoundException ex)
                {
                    throw new PlatformNotSupportedException(
                        "libudev is not available on this system. Hotplug support requires libudev. " +
                        "Please use LibInputContextType.Path instead.", ex);
                }
            }
            else
            {
                ctx = libinput_path_create_context();
                if (ctx == IntPtr.Zero)
                {
                    throw new InvalidOperationException("Failed to initialize libinput path context.");
                }
            }

            _inputThread = new Thread(() => InputThread(ctx, options, udevCtx, _cts.Token))
            {
                Name = "Input Manager Worker",
                IsBackground = true
            };
            _inputThread.Start();
        }

        public void SetInputRoot(IInputRoot root)
        {
            _inputRoot = root;
        }

        public void Dispose()
        {
            if (_cts != null)
            {
                _cts.Cancel();
                _cts.Dispose();
                _cts = null;
            }

            // Wait briefly for the thread to finish and release native resources
            _inputThread?.Join(500);
        }
    }
}

  // --- P/Invokes for Udev and LibInput Udev extensions ---

        [DllImport(LibUdev, EntryPoint = "udev_new", CallingConvention = CallingConvention.Cdecl)]
        private static extern IntPtr udev_new();

        [DllImport(LibUdev, EntryPoint = "udev_unref", CallingConvention = CallingConvention.Cdecl)]
        private static extern IntPtr udev_unref(IntPtr udev);

        // Note: We assume LibInputInterface and s_Interface are defined in the other partial class of LibInputNativeUnsafeMethods
        [DllImport(LibInput, EntryPoint = "libinput_udev_create_context", CallingConvention = CallingConvention.Cdecl)]
        private static extern IntPtr libinput_udev_create_context(in LibInputInterface iface, IntPtr user_data, IntPtr udev);

        [DllImport(LibInput, EntryPoint = "libinput_udev_assign_seat", CallingConvention = CallingConvention.Cdecl)]
        private static extern int libinput_udev_assign_seat(IntPtr ctx, [MarshalAs(UnmanagedType.LPUTF8Str)] string seat);

        [DllImport(LibInput, EntryPoint = "libinput_event_get_device", CallingConvention = CallingConvention.Cdecl)]
        private static extern IntPtr libinput_event_get_device(IntPtr ev);

        [DllImport(LibInput, EntryPoint = "libinput_unref", CallingConvention = CallingConvention.Cdecl)]
        private static extern void libinput_unref(IntPtr ctx);

        // --------------------------------------------------------
```
